| **JVM Memory** | `-Xmx1536m` (1.5 GB max heap) |
| **AndroidX** | `true` (modern Android support libs) |
| **Minification** | `false` (not using ProGuard for release) |
| **BouncyCastle** | Pinned to `1.76` (avoids Java 21 bytecode issues) |

### 19.5 Web-to-Native Bridge (Capacitor Architecture)

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Android Native Layer"
        A[MainActivity.java]
        B[WebView]
        C[Native GPS Plugin]
    end

    subgraph "Web Layer (inside WebView)"
        D[React App - dist/]
        E["@capacitor/geolocation JS API"]
        F[Firebase SDK]
    end

    D --> E
    E -->|Bridge Call| C
    C -->|Native GPS Data| E
    E -->|Position Object| D
    D --> F

    A --> B
    B --> D
```

### 19.6 Capacitor vs React Native — Why Capacitor?

| Feature | Capacitor | React Native |
|---------|-----------|--------------|
| **Code Reuse** | 100% web code reused | Need to rewrite in RN components |
| **Learning Curve** | Minimal (it's just web) | Steep (new component paradigm) |
| **Performance** | Good for content apps | Better for animation-heavy apps |
| **Plugin Access** | Native via JS bridge | Native modules |
| **Web Support** | Built-in (same codebase) | Separate web project needed |
| **Bundle Size** | Larger (WebView overhead) | Smaller native views |
| **Best For** | Apps that are already web-first | Apps built native-first |

> UniTrack was **built as a website first** (Semester 3), so Capacitor was the natural choice — zero rewrite needed.

