## 34. Additional Viva Questions & Answers

---

**Q11: What are the minimum device requirements for this app?**

> The Android APK requires Android 5.1 (API 22) or higher with GPS hardware. On web, any modern browser (Chrome 80+, Firefox 78+) with JavaScript enabled, location access, and internet connectivity is required. A device needs at minimum 1 GB RAM and any internet connection.

---

**Q12: How does the app handle poor GPS signals?**

> The GPS API provides an `accuracy` field in meters — we display this to drivers (e.g., "±8m"). If a GPS fix isn't obtained within 15 seconds, a timeout error is shown. The default speed of 25 km/h is used when the device reports 0 speed (stationary). For students, the `maximumAge` parameter allows reusing cached positions up to 60 seconds old.

---

**Q13: What Android permissions does the app require?**

> Three permissions: `INTERNET` (auto-granted, for Firebase), `ACCESS_COARSE_LOCATION` (Wi-Fi/cell location), and `ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION` (GPS). The app also declares `android.hardware.location.gps` as a required hardware feature, meaning devices without GPS hardware won't see the app on Google Play.

---

**Q14: How does the bulk import from Excel work?**

> The admin uploads an Excel or CSV file. We parse it using the SheetJS library (client-side, no server upload needed). Column headers are normalized to handle variations (e.g., "Roll No", "roll_no", "enrollment"). Each row is validated for required fields and checked for duplicate emails/roll numbers within the file. Users are then created sequentially with a 100ms delay between each to avoid Firebase rate limiting. A progress bar shows real-time status, and failed entries can be downloaded as a CSV error report.

---

**Q15: What happens if two drivers broadcast from the same device?**

> Each driver writes to `busLocations/{their-own-uid}`. Firebase Security Rules enforce `auth.uid == $driverId`, so Driver A cannot write to Driver B's location node. If a driver logs out and another logs in on the same device, the new driver writes to their own separate node. The previous driver's node is cleaned up when they go "offline" (setting `isActive: false`).

---

**Q16: How does the schedule template system save time for admins?**

> Instead of manually creating a schedule entry for every day, an admin creates a template once (e.g., "Driver X + Bus Y + Route Z, Monday–Friday"). The `generateDates()` function computes all matching dates in a given range, and `generateScheduleEntries()` creates a Firestore document for each. A semester has ~90 weekdays — the template generates 90 schedules in one click instead of 90 manual entries.

---

**Q17: What is the Vibration API and where do you use it?**

> The Web Vibration API (`navigator.vibrate()`) provides haptic feedback on mobile devices. We use 11 different vibration patterns: light tap for UI interactions, double pulse when going online, celebration pattern when completing a route, and warning pattern for alerts. It's checked with `'vibrate' in navigator` and silently skipped on unsupported devices.

---

**Q18: How does your map caching work for offline use?**

> The Vite PWA plugin generates a Service Worker that caches map tiles using a `CacheFirst` strategy. When a student views a map area, all tile images are stored in the browser cache (up to 500 tiles, 30-day expiry). If the user loses internet, previously viewed map areas still display from cache. New areas won't load until connectivity returns.

---

**Q19: Why did you use Vite instead of Create React App (CRA)?**

> Create React App is deprecated by the React team since 2023. Vite is the recommended replacement because it offers: 10x faster dev server startup (ESBuild-based), Hot Module Replacement (HMR), native ES module serving, tree-shaking, and built-in PWA plugin support. CRA bundles with Webpack which is significantly slower.

---

**Q20: What data does Firebase store in the free Spark plan? Are there limits?**

> Firebase Spark plan includes: 1 GB Firestore storage, 10 GB/month bandwidth, 50K reads/day, 20K writes/day, 20K deletes/day. For RTDB: 1 GB storage, 10 GB/month bandwidth, 200 simultaneous connections. For Auth: unlimited users. For Hosting: 10 GB storage, 360 MB/day bandwidth. For a university of ~500 students with ~10 drivers, this is more than sufficient.

